Problem Background

¶

Define $S_p(x) := \sum_{a \leq x} \left( \frac{a}{p} \right)$ to be the character sum of legendre symbols. In other words, the character sum is the partial sum of Legendre symbols. A famous inequality, known as the Polya-Vinogradov Inequality, gives us the following bound: $$ |S_p(x)| \leq \sqrt{p} \log p. $$ One way to prove this involves using Polya's Fourier Expansion : $$ S_p(x) = \frac{G(p)}{2\pi i} \sum_{i \leq |n| \leq H} \left( \frac{n}{p} \right) \frac{[1 - e(\frac{-nx}{p})]}{n} + O\left(\frac{p \log p}{H}\right) + O(1), $$ where $$ G(p) = \begin{cases} \sqrt{p} & \text{ if } p \equiv 1 \ (\textrm{mod } 4) \\ i \sqrt{p} & \text{ if } p \equiv -1 \ (\textrm{mod } 4). \end{cases} $$

It turns out if you instantiate $H = (\log p)^2$, you get the following: $$ S_p(x) = C\sqrt{p} \cdot \log \log p + O\left(\frac{p}{\log p}\right). $$ Notice that if the error term is smaller than we improve the Polya-Vinogradov Inequality! This is the ambitious ultimate goal, and a starting point was to generate numerics to see what this error term actually looks like, which is what this notebook showcases.

Data Description

¶

First let's go through a bit of notation. We let $S(x)$ be the character sum of legendre symbols, and $F(x)$ be the main term of Polya's Fourier Expansion. We are interested in the max (or min) of $$D(x) := S(x) - F(x).$$

Specifically, I collected data for around $135$ primes, with $2$ being around $1,000,000$ and the rest being sampled uniformly at random from $100,000- 200,000$. For each prime $p$ I record the following pieces of info:

  • prime : p

  • pos_error : max(D(x))

  • neg_error : min(D(x))
  • x_pos_error : 100 * (argmax(D(x)) / prime)
  • x_neg_error : 100 * (argmin(D(x)) / prime)
  • max_error : max(pos_error, -1 $\cdot$ neg_error)
  • max_error_ind: 1 if max_error == pos_error else 0
  • x_max_error : x_pos_error if max_error_ind == 1 else x_neg_error
  • mag_diff : |pos_error + neg_error|
  • dist_check : |100 - x_pos_error - x_neg_error|
  • mod_4 : prime (mod 4)

Additionally, I also create a "diff plot", which is simply a scatterplot of $D(x)$ vs. $x$.

Most of these are intuitive things to look at. It doesn't really make sense to look at mag_diff or dist_check, though it will be clear by the exploratory data analysis (EDA) that this is a natural thing to study. Further, it turns out that mod_4 is the most important feature; the diff plots become much clearer when considering this feature.

def plot(prime = None, name = None):
    if prime is None and name is None:
        raise ValueError("At least one of prime and name shouldn't be None")
    
    if isinstance(prime, str):
        name = prime
        prime = None
        
    plot_path = os.path.join(path, "plots")

    if prime is None:
        plot = f"{plot_path}/{name}.png"
        if not os.path.exists(plot):
            raise IOError("Plot path doesn't exist")

    if name is None:
        plot = f"{plot_path}/Prime = {prime} Difference Plot.png"
        if not os.path.exists(plot):
            raise IOError(f"Prime = {prime} hasn't been analyzed yet")
        
    img = Image.open(plot)
    plt.figure(figsize = (20, 10))
    plt.imshow(img)
    plt.axis('off')
    plt.show()


lst_path = os.path.join(path, 'data')
get_lst_path = lambda prime : f'{lst_path}/Prime = {prime} Diff List.txt'

def get_lst(prime):
    path = get_lst_path(prime)

    with open(path, "r") as txt_file:
        lst = txt_file.read().splitlines()

    return [float(x) for x in lst]

Analysis:

  • We expected no vertical translation on the primes == 1 (mod 4)
  • In reality they are almost exactly 0 (up to $> 15$ decimal places)
  • We expected varying vertical translation on the primes == 3 (mod 4)
  • In reality they have varying vertical translation (mean error $\neq 0$)

Symmetry Check:

We have checked the translation property, and now it's time to check symmetry. Let $D$ be a difference list and $D(i)$ be the ith element of $D$. Then we get the following:

  • Symmetry $\implies D(i) - D(-i) \approx 0$
  • Antisymmetry $\implies D(i) + D(-i) \approx 0$

So, to check this we will compute the following:

  • Sym Check: plot i vs. $D(i) + D(-i)$
  • AntiSym Check: plot i vs. $D(i) - D(-i)$

We expect the following:

  • Sym Check plot $\approx 0$ for primes $\equiv 3\ (\mathrm{mod}\ 4)$
  • AntiSym Check plot $\approx 0$ for primes $\equiv 1\ (\mathrm{mod}\ 4)$.

Conclusion

¶

Essentially I found that the error always seems to stay within $O(\log p)$ (works if big-O constant is on the order of $10$). I also found that looking at the primes mod $4$ has a strange relations with translations and symmetries. However, it's important to not extrapolate too much.

In [109]:
plot(1020389)
In [110]:
plot(1000003)

Plot Analysis:

  • Here are two diff plots for primes on the order of 1 million
  • These, in contrast with smaller primes (100-200k), seem to have errors disproportionately higher
  • In other words the behavior we see at 100-200k is definitely not convergent behavior
  • Thus it's possible the error continues to grow or even explodes later on

We are interested in the max error and bounding that. The error seems to come from two components: one is the vertical translation (if you vertical translate up you have high error), one is the pseudorandom error (there are seemingly random spikes that can cause high error). So which of these is the dominating effect?
